
* The ~GNU Emacs~ configuration
This is a complete configuration for GNU Emacs 24. This is a fairly heavy emacs configuration - for integration with the StumpWM window manager, gmail, irc, and web browsing, all within GNU emacs - in no way do I recommend anyone else use this configuration. But for those foolish enough, you can contact me [[email:mathew.ball@gmail.com][here]]. Fort this project, the ~emacs-dir~ directory for the project is split into multiple files; each file providing a specific set of behaviours - initiation, appearance, general, user (i.e. downloaded from MELPA), writing, programming, and some key-bindings for convenience.

This configuration presents the /best[fn:best]/ environment for using emacs either for writing prose, or writing code. The availability of the many extensions for emacs with the inclusion of package.el has made the process of discovering emacs extensions trivial. For this reason, this configuration makes /extensive/ use of the package.el archives.

Emacs is extensible, and many hackers have contributed extensions which would fall outside the classification of a "text-editor"; things such as a fully-featured email client, an IRC client, a directory editor, a shell, a web browser, a bibliography manager; and many new extensions being contributed daily.

** [[file:init.el][Initiation]]
This file initialises the configuration:

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20user%20variables][user variables]]
Define two customisation groups: [[elisp:(customize-group%20user-variables)][user-variables]] and [[elisp:(customize-group%20'user-directories)][user-directories]].

Each customisation group includes a number of variables, these variables are mainly used by org-mode or for interaction with a StumpWM environment.

Sets the user details (name and email address).

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20common%20lisp][common lisp]]
Require common-lisp library.

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20after%20macro][after macro]]
Define a macro [[file:init.el::(defmacro%20after%20(mode%20&rest%20body)][after]] which loads the body code after its argument file (syntactic sugar over [[help:eval-after-load][eval-after-load]]).

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20load%20path][load path]]
Modifies the load-path variable.

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20info%20path][info path]]
Modifies the info-path variable.

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20package%20manager][package manager]]
This project is designed for use with the following emacs lisp packages. They are all available on [[http://melpa.milkbox.net/#/][MELPA]] using package.el[fn:ELPA] to install.

This package list is defined in the file [[file:init.el::(ensure-package-installed][init.el]]. The following files[fn:auto-setup] are automatically installed if not found (generally the first time the setup is run):

- adaptive-wrap :: Uses the emacs display engine to create "virtual indentation" which aligns lists correctly (but doesn't modify the buffer).
- auto-complete :: Provides "intellisense" like functionality.
- browse-kill-ring :: Browse the kill-ring interactively.
- dash
- diminish :: Configure how minor-modes are displayed in the mode-line.
- ebib :: Bibliography database system.
- elisp-slime-nav :: Slime-like navigation for emacs lisp.
- epl
- erc-hl-nicks :: Highlight user's nicknames with ERC.
- flx :: Better flex matching.
- flx-ido :: Improved flex algorithm for ido.
- geiser
- gh :: Library interacting with the GitHub API.
- gist :: Paste code snippets to gist.github.com and return link.
- git-commit-mode
- git-rebase-mode
- google-translate :: Translate user input from chosen language into chosen language.
- haskell-mode :: Major-mode for programming in Haskell.
- ibuffer-vc :: Display version-control status in ibuffer.
- ido-ubiquitous :: Enable ido everywhere.
- logito :: Logging library.
- magit :: Interact with git projects.
- org-journal :: Journal functionality utilising org-mode.
- paredit :: Intelligent parenthesis editing.
- pcache
- pkg-info
- popup
- rainbow-delimiters :: Modify the foreground colour face for pairs of delimiters.
- smex :: Super-charge M-x.
- sr-speedbar :: Speedbar in single frame.
- s
- tabulated-list
- undo-tree :: Tree interface to the undo system.
- w3m :: Emacs interface to w3m text web-browser.
- ya snippet :: Yet Another Snippet system.

For most packages, I modify their default behaviour; their respective settings are set in the file [[file:config-el/user-config.el][user-config.el]].

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20use%20configuration%20files][use configuration files]]
Define function [[file:init.el::(defun%20use-config-file%20(name)][use-config-file]] to load in an elisp library.

Requires specific configuration files[fn:order-of-evaluation]:
 - *appearance-config*
 - *general-config*
 - *user-config*
 - *writing-config*
 - *programming-config*
 - *key-bindings-config*

An explanation for each of these files, and the respective configuration they provide, follows in the text.

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20shutdown%20emacs%20server][shutdown emacs server]]
Provide the user with the command [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20COMMENT:%20shutdown%20emacs%20server][server-shutdown]]. This will save any (modified) buffers, save the emacs daemon process, and kill the server.

*** [[file:init.el::%3B%3B%3B%20IMPORTANT:%20customize%20configuration%20file][customize configuration file]]
Set the custom configuration file (so that it doesn't populate this file with customisations).

